  "body": "(Updated the table)\r\n\r\n### Issue\r\nBy observing Lighthouse testnet status, I just realized that the validators dequeue rate is `MIN_PER_EPOCH_CHURN_LIMIT/2` per epoch instead of `MIN_PER_EPOCH_CHURN_LIMIT` per epoch.\r\n\r\nIt's because the current `process_registry_updates` function first selected the eligible 4 validators sorted by `activation_eligibility_epoch`, and then update the `validator.activation_epoch` (if `validator.activation_epoch == FAR_FUTURE_EPOCH`). However, it may select **the same validators** as the previous round.\r\n\r\nThe current code:\r\n```python\r\n    # Queue validators eligible for activation and not dequeued for activation prior to finalized epoch\r\n    activation_queue = sorted([\r\n        index for index, validator in enumerate(state.validators)\r\n        if validator.activation_eligibility_epoch != FAR_FUTURE_EPOCH\r\n        and validator.activation_epoch >= compute_activation_exit_epoch(state.finalized_checkpoint.epoch)\r\n    ], key=lambda index: state.validators[index].activation_eligibility_epoch)\r\n    # Dequeued validators for activation up to churn limit (without resetting activation epoch)\r\n    for index in activation_queue[:get_validator_churn_limit(state)]:\r\n        validator = state.validators[index]\r\n        if validator.activation_epoch == FAR_FUTURE_EPOCH:\r\n            validator.activation_epoch = compute_activation_exit_epoch(get_current_epoch(state))\r\n```\r\n\r\nTo make it easier to understand, here is the scenario:\r\n1. At epoch `816`:\r\n    * 16 validators get set activation eligibility. `validator.activation_eligibility_epoch` = `816`.\r\n    * 4 validators get selected to `activation_queue`.\r\n    * These validators got set `validator.activation_epoch` to `821`\r\n2. At epoch `817`:\r\n    * Since we sort the queue by `key=lambda index: state.validators[index].activation_eligibility_epoch`, the tiebreaker key may be validator index. So **the same** `4` validators get selected to `activation_queue`. (Their `activation_epoch = 821` is greater than or equal to `compute_activation_exit_epoch(finalized_epoch) = 820`, matching the condition). \r\n    * Since `validator.activation_epoch` != `FAR_FUTURE_EPOCH`, **no validators' `activation_epoch` would be changed**.\r\n\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9263930/70531976-05d0cf80-1b91-11ea-8811-d1e996ff3858.png)\r\n\r\nSo with a bunch of validators in the waiting queue, more than half of the epochs (depending on finalization) couldn't dequeue any validator. That's very inefficient.\r\n\r\n### Proposed solution\r\n1. Should we set condition to `validator.activation_eligibility_epoch >= compute_activation_exit_epoch(state.finalized_checkpoint.epoch)` instead of `validator.activation_epoch >= compute_activation_exit_epoch(state.finalized_checkpoint.epoch)`?\r\n2.  Check if `validator.activation_epoch == FAR_FUTURE_EPOCH` in the filter.\r\n\r\nIf so, it can be changed to:\r\n```python\r\n    # Queue validators eligible for activation and not dequeued for activation prior to finalized epoch\r\n    activation_queue = sorted([\r\n        index for index, validator in enumerate(state.validators)\r\n        if validator.activation_epoch == FAR_FUTURE_EPOCH\r\n        and validator.activation_eligibility_epoch >= compute_activation_exit_epoch(state.finalized_checkpoint.epoch)\r\n    ], key=lambda index: state.validators[index].activation_eligibility_epoch)\r\n    # Dequeued validators for activation up to churn limit\r\n    for index in activation_queue[:get_validator_churn_limit(state)]:\r\n        validator = state.validators[index]\r\n        validator.activation_epoch = compute_activation_exit_epoch(get_current_epoch(state))\r\n```\r\n",
